    <text>
        <body>
            
            <div1 type="letter">
                
                <pb facs="nei.j4a.7.36-38_0001" />
                
                <fw type="letterhead">
                    <hi rend="caps">THE RADIANT LIFE PRESS</hi>
                        <lb/>
                    George Wharton James, Propr.
                        <lb/>
                    1098 North Raymond Avenue
                        <lb/>
                    
                    <hi rend="caps">PASADENA, CAL.,</hi></fw> <opener><dateline>Mar 10. 1920.</dateline>
                
                    <salute>My Dear Mr. Neihardt</salute>
                </opener>
                <p>I've been away + find your letter waiting for an answer on my desk.</p>
                
                <p>Am sending you today the best I have of the Jan Gabriel mission + also the Mohave Desert. Can get you another <unclear>print</unclear> of <hi rend="underline">Mohave</hi> showing the Joshua trees or Yucca Mohaviensis. Shall I do so? Please spell Mohave + Navaho in the simple American fashion. Also <hi rend="underline">Canyon</hi>. Why should we persist in using an alien spelling for <hi rend="underline">our own</hi> + thus confuse our people as to the proper pronunciation. While Mohave + Navaho
                
                    <fw type="curatorial">36</fw>
                    
                    <pb facs="nei.j4a.7.36-38_0002"/>
                    
                    <fw type="curatorial">37</fw>
                
                are <hi rend="underline">proper</hi> names they are indigenous to the <hi rend="caps">U.S.</hi> Spanish names of Spanish places + persons we must accept, but <hi rend="underline">why</hi> of American places + persons. And as to <hi rend="underline">Cañon</hi>&#8212; it is a curse + an abomination to hundreds of thousands who don't know the meaning of the tilda &#8212; + why should they? Though reasonably educated, they ought not to be expected to know the "idio<hi rend="triple underline">t</hi>syncrasies" of every European language.</p>
                
                <p>I shall be thankful if you will help in this fight for a rational simplicity.</p>
                <closer>
                    <salute>Cordially yours</salute>
                    
                    <signed>George Wharton James</signed>
                </closer>
                    
                <postscript><p>The prints have cost me .45¢ each, except the 5x7 35¢.</p></postscript>
                
                    <pb facs="nei.j4a.7.36-38_0003"/>
                
                <fw type="letterhead">
                    <hi rend="caps">THE RADIANT LIFE PRESS</hi>
                        <lb/>
                    George Wharton James, Propr.
                        <lb/>
                    1098 North Raymond Avenue
                        <lb/>
                    
                    <hi rend="caps">PASADENA, CAL.,</hi>_____________________________
                </fw>
                
                <postscript><p>After consideration I have decided to send you several of the missions. Perhaps the <hi rend="underline">Santa Clara</hi> from a family by my friend, <hi rend="underline">Andrew <hi rend="caps">P.</hi> Hill</hi>, will give your readers a better idea of the early days.</p></postscript>
                
                    <fw type="curatorial">31</fw>
                
            </div1>
        </body>
        
